{
  "chapterTitle": "House 6",
  "notes": "This section describes the inhabitants and divine hierarchy of the temple, emphasizing the sheer number of people (ten by ten) and the celestial and earthly roles of its deities.",
  "chunks": [
    {
      "originalText": "e2 lu2 10-e 10-e nam-mi-in-tuc\ne2 kecki-ka lu2 10-e 10-e nam-mi-in-tuc\n",
      "translatedText": "The house where ten by ten the people dwell within its gate,\nThe house of Kesh where ten by ten the people congregate.\n",
      "type": "verse"
    },
    {
      "originalText": "lugal-bi ucumgal-am3 an-na dirig-ga\nnin-bi dnin-hur-saj-ja2-am3 gu2 ki-ce3 ma-al\n",
      "translatedText": "Its king is like a dragon great, who floats across the sky,\nIts lady is Ninhursag, who to earth bows low and nigh.\n",
      "type": "verse"
    },
    {
      "originalText": "e2 ensi2-bi dacac7-gi4-am3\nnu-gig-bi dnin-tud-ra\n",
      "translatedText": "The governor of this great house is Ashgi, bold and strong,\nIts high priestess is Nintud, to whom all births belong.\n",
      "type": "verse"
    },
    {
      "originalText": "kecki-gin7 rib-ba lu2 ci-in-ga-tum2-mu\nur-saj-bi dacac7-gi4-gin7 rib-ba ama ci-in-ga-u3-tud\nnin-bi dnin-tud-gin7 rib-ba-ra a-ba-a igi mu-ni-in-du8\n",
      "translatedText": "Will any man bring forth a thing so great as Kesh has been?\nWill any mother bear a hero like Ashgi, so bold?\nWho has seen a lady like Nintud, of beauty untold?\n",
      "type": "verse"
    },
    {
      "originalText": "e2 6-kam-ma",
      "translatedText": "The sixth house.",
      "type": "verse"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "chapterTitle": "House 7",
  "notes": "This section focuses on the musical and ritual life within the temple, highlighting the instruments and the divine atmosphere of the ceremonies.",
  "chunks": [
    {
      "originalText": "e2 u3-tud kug-ga cag4-bi a-ba mu-zu\ne2 kecki u3-tud kug-ga cag4-bi a-ba mu-zu",
      "translatedText": "The house of holy birth—who knows its inner heart?\nThe house of Kesh, of holy birth—who knows its inner heart?",
